result.execSummary:
The defendant was charged with both OWI (3rd) and Operating w/ PAC (3rd). The defendant was found guilty of OWI (3rd) and the other charge, Operating w/ PAC (3rd) was dismissed by the court.

  • Terry Prather Jr was found guilty of OWI (3rd), an unclassified misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 346.63(1)(a).
  • Terry Prather Jr was found guilty of Go Armed with Firearm While Intoxicated, a class A misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 941.20(1)(b).

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Notice of Right to Seek Postconviction Relief received and filed.

Defendant Terry Prather in court with attorney Scott r Winkler.  Katherine M Halopka-Ivery appeared for the State of Wisconsin.

As to Counts ONE and Three: 

Defendant waived rights and pled guilty.  Guilty Plea Questionnaire received and filed.  Defendant examined as to the plea.  Parties stipulate to the facts of the complaint as a basis for a guilty plea.  Court found the defendant guilty as charged in the complaint.  Judgment of Conviction entered.

On motion of the State, Court ordererd Count TWO:  Dismissed.

AS TO COUNT ONE:

The Court ordered the Defendant to serve FIVE MONTHS  in the House of Correction, consecutive to any other sentence with credit for ONE  day time served.  Huber privileges pursuant to Sec. 303.08 Wis. Stats to apply FOR WORK. SENTENCE TO COMMENCE FORTHWITH. COURT OBJECTS TO ES. 
  Fine of $1500.00 including  all mandatory costs, fees and surcharges  to be paid FORTHWITH or serve 20 CONSECUTIVE days in the House of Correction.

Court ordered defendant's operating privileges revoked for TWO YEARS with the mandatory reinstatement fee.

Defendant's operating privilege for operation of Class D vehicles is restricted to operating vehicles that are equipped with an ignition interlock device; and each motor vehicle for which the defendant's name appears on the vehicle's certificate of title or registration must be equipped with an ignition interlock device beginning on the date the department issues any license and for a period of  TWO YEARS thereafter.
